04561nam a22007215i 9780801469701DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013954740  a97808014697017 a10.7591/97808014697012doi  a(DE-B1597)478673  a(OCoLC)979630556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ200.B4bS65 2016 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a306.740943090342231 aSmith, Jill Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBerlin Coquette :bProstitution and the New German Woman, 1890–1933 /cJill Suzanne Smith. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Berlin’s Bourgeois Whores -- t1. Sex, Money, and Marriage: Prostitution as an Instrument of Conjugal Critique -- t2. Righteous Women and Lost Girls: Radical Bourgeois Feminists and the Fight for Moral Reform -- t3. Naughty Berlin? New Women, New Spaces, and Erotic Confusion -- t4. Working Girls: White-Collar Workers and Prostitutes in Late Weimar Fiction -- tConclusion: Berlin Coquette -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the late nineteenth century the city of Berlin developed such a reputation for lawlessness and sexual licentiousness that it came to be known as the "Whore of Babylon." Out of this reputation for debauchery grew an unusually rich discourse around prostitution. In Berlin Coquette, Jill Suzanne Smith shows how this discourse transcended the usual clichés about prostitutes and actually explored complex visions of alternative moralities or sexual countercultures including the "New Morality" articulated by feminist radicals, lesbian love, and the "New Woman."Combining extensive archival research with close readings of a broad spectrum of texts and images from the late Wilhelmine and Weimar periods, Smith recovers a surprising array of productive discussions about extramarital sexuality, women's financial autonomy, and respectability. She highlights in particular the figure of the cocotte (Kokotte), a specific type of prostitute who capitalized on the illusion of respectable or upstanding womanhood and therefore confounded easy categorization. By exploring the semantic connections between the figure of the cocotte and the act of flirtation (of being coquette), Smith’s work presents flirtation as a type of social interaction through which both prostitutes and non-prostitutes in Imperial and Weimar Berlin could express extramarital sexual desire and agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aProstitutionzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstitutionzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aUrban Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801469701zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801469701/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK